{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16008"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16008"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73467"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8699"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58936"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"},{"type":"tags","id":"8735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20815"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73467"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, specialised regions of surface ectoderm thicken to form placodes. These structures are crucial for sensory organ development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the developmental fate of nasal placodes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develop into neural crest cells","Form the nasal cartilage","Give rise to otic vesicles","Develop into olfactory epithelium","Form the nasal septum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal placodes\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised thickenings of surface ectoderm that appear during week 4 of embryonic development on the frontonasal prominence. They \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelop into olfactory epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E through invagination to form nasal pits, which later develop into the nasal chambers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment into neural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - nasal placodes develop from surface ectoderm, while neural crest cells arise from neural ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of nasal cartilage\u003C/strong\u003E occurs from neural crest cells, not nasal placodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment into otic vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E occurs from otic placodes, which are distinct from nasal placodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of the nasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E occurs from mesenchymal tissue, not from nasal placodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nasal placodes are essential for the development of the olfactory system and ultimately give rise to the specialised sensory epithelium responsible for smell.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nasal placodes are thickened regions of ectoderm that develop into the olfactory epithelium.","Nasal placodes appear in week 4 of embryonic development on the frontonasal prominence.","Nasal placodes invaginate to form nasal pits which later develop into nasal chambers."],"references":["Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Els